{
  "doc_id": "44485",
  "text": "Sedimentation patterns in alpine and temperate lakes can be strongly influenced by the magnitude and physical properties of river inflows [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In particular, increased river inflow in response to rainfall and the spring freshet can form gravity currents carrying large sediment loads into lakes [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Seasonal variability in river-fed lakes can influence sedimentation and produce clastic varves, e.g. relatively thick layers of coarse sediment during summer and thinner layers of fine sediments during winter (e.g. [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . In order to use clastic varves to reconstruct past climate, establishing the linkages between meteorological, limnological and sedimentary processes in lakes is required (e.g. [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . Lake-monitoring programs provide measurements of physical properties in the water column (e.g. temperature, river inflow, velocities) and sediment characteristics (e.g. turbidity, particle concentration, particle size) that can help identify the control processes on sedimentation and to accurately interpret the sedimentary record preserved in the lake bed [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] .",
